{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Reiner Schürmann’s account of perigrinal ontology from the perspective of Meister Eckhart illuminates the depth and nuance of human relationships.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Professor Schürmann totalizes the relationship between the will and the intellect and unites the different categories of Platonic philosophy under the concept of perigrinal ontology.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Instead of treating epistemology or aesthetics in isolation, they are examined as they relate to ontology.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Meister Eckhart’s writings and personal commitment to that project are noteworthy in this context.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "The absolute absence of the faculty of the will in Meister Eckhart’s work distinguished him from these other philosophies.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Schürmann’s exposition of Meister Eckhart’s philosophy is grounded in a comprehensive understanding of Plato.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Perigrinal ontology reflects a different approach to ontology—the study of being per se.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The disturbing power of Eckhart’s theory of releasement consists precisely in the transformation of a psychological or moral concept into an ontological one.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Detachment for Eckhart consists not only in riddance of representation but entails a qualitative or positive change.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Schürmann’s account of original ontology should be understood in the following way: Like the peregrine falcon, the self is best thought of as constantly 'underway.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Unlike other non-essentialist philosophies, such as Jean-Paul Sartre’s, owing to one’s radical freedom, one is not fleeing from identification with things.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Eckhart wants us to think that beyond all distinctions, limitations, and oppositions, there is simply What is—the One.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Detachment in Meister Eckhart has a radical element to it—it locates the basis for existence in an unfurling of the intellect and cognition.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The understood subject and the understanding subject are one being, just as the sensed object and the sensing subject are one being.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Relational praxis comprises Meister Eckhart's ontology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "The detached individual enters a different temporality. It is the eternal moment, and one shares the same time as God.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Schürmann’s cautions against syncretism have been addressed by several authors since Meister Eckhart’s Mystic and Philosopher was published.",
      "label": "premise"
    }
  },
